Heatmap for patient stratification

Heatmap for patient stratification

  • R environment
  • Load the human TIL CD8 reference from FigShare.
  • Heatmap plot examples

P. Gueguen, M. Andreatta and S. Carmona

2023-01-23

This short tutorial shows how to use the make.heatmap function from ProjecTILs to display averaged gene expressions from Seurat objects, split by clusters, patients, or any kind of metadata.

R environment

First, lets check package dependencies.

Sys.setenv(R_REMOTES_NO_ERRORS_FROM_WARNINGS = "true")
options(timeout = max(900, getOption("timeout")))

if (!requireNamespace("renv")) install.packages("renv")
library(renv)
renv::restore()
* The library is already synchronized with the lockfile.
library(ProjecTILs)
library(Seurat)
library(tidyr)
library(pheatmap)

Load the human TIL CD8 reference from FigShare.

ref <- load.reference.map(ref = "https://figshare.com/ndownloader/files/38921366")
[1] "Trying to download custom reference from https://figshare.com/ndownloader/files/38921366..."
[1] "Loading Custom Reference Atlas..."
[1] "Loaded Custom Reference map Human CD8 TILs"

Heatmap plot examples

Now we can use this reference as our input Seurat object to test the different functions from make.heatmap. Lets have a first look at the default plotting behavior. We need to provide at least one metadata to display on the heatmap using the metadata argument.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    metadata = c("orig.ident", "Tissue"))

We can give the reference used to fix the colors and order of the clusters used, with the ref parameter.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    ref = ref, metadata = c("orig.ident", "Tissue"))

We can select the minimum number of cells a sample should have to be considered using the min.cells parameter. This value is set at 10 cells by default.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    ref = ref, metadata = c("orig.ident", "Tissue"), min.cells = 100)

We can also decide to order the heatmap by specific metadata columns with order.by parameter. Lets see how it looks.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    ref = ref, metadata = c("orig.ident", "Tissue"), order.by = "Tissue")

By default, samples with metadata as NA will be removed, but we can remove this parameter with remove.NA.meta = FALSE, as shown here with the cloneType metadata.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    ref = ref, metadata = c("cloneType", "Tissue"), order.by = "Tissue", remove.NA.meta = F)

Genes and samples can be clustered with cluster_genes and cluster_samples parameters. By default, we use the Ward.D2 method for clustering.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    ref = ref, metadata = c("cloneType", "Tissue"), order.by = "Tissue", cluster_genes = T,
    cluster_samples = T)

Finally, we can also change the metadata palette if we input a list of palette in the correct format in palette parameter. If needed, the clusters colors can be changed using the name Subtype from the list of palettes.

my.palettes <- list()

# Setup Subtype colors with functional.cluster metadata
my.palettes[["Subtype"]] <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(n = 8, name = "Set3"))(length(levels(ref$functional.cluster)))
names(my.palettes[["Subtype"]]) <- levels(ref$functional.cluster)

# Setup cloneType metadata colors
ref$cloneType <- factor(ref$cloneType)
my.palettes[["cloneType"]] <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(n = 8, name = "Pastel1"))(length(levels(ref$cloneType)))
names(my.palettes[["cloneType"]]) <- levels(ref$cloneType)

# Setup Tissue metadata colors
ref$Tissue <- factor(ref$Tissue)
my.palettes[["Tissue"]] <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(n = 8, name = "Pastel2"))(length(levels(ref$Tissue)))
names(my.palettes[["Tissue"]]) <- levels(ref$Tissue)

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    metadata = c("cloneType", "Tissue"), order.by = "Tissue", palette = my.palettes)

You can now display the averaged expression heatmap with multiple metadata on one single plot.

make.heatmap(ref, genes = c("LEF1", "CCR7", "GZMK", "FGFBP2", "XCL1", "HAVCR2", "KLRB1"),
    ref = ref, metadata = c("cloneType", "Tissue", "Type", "orig.ident"), order.by = "Tissue")
